solution: ```class Solution {
public:
    long long waysToBuyPensPencils(int total, int cost1, int cost2) {
        long long res = 0;
        if (cost1 == 0 && cost2 == 0) return 1LL * (total + 1) * (total + 1);
        if (cost1 == 0) return 1LL * (total / cost2 + 1) * (total + 1);
        if (cost2 == 0) return 1LL * (total / cost1 + 1) * (total + 1);

        for (long long pens = 0; pens * cost1 <= total; ++pens) {
            long long rem = total - pens * cost1;
            res += rem / cost2 + 1;
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(total / cost1)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Iterate over every possible count of pens (0 to total/cost1). For each count, the remaining money determines how many pencils can be bought (0 to rem/cost2), giving rem/cost2 + 1 choices. Summing these counts yields the answer. The loop runs at most 10^6 iterations, which is trivial for modern CPUs.

